{"title_page": "James McIlroy (surgeon)", "text_new": "'''James Archibald McIlroy''' (3 November 1879 &ndash; 27 July 1968<ref name=endurance>{{cite web|title=James Archibald McIlroy|url=http://www.enduranceobituaries.co.uk/mcilroy.htm|work=enduranceobituaries.co.uk|accessdate=3 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306064659/http://www.enduranceobituaries.co.uk/mcilroy.htm|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref>) was a British [[surgeon]] and a member of [[Ernest Shackleton]]'s crew on the [[Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition]] (1914-1916). \n\n==Early life and career==\nHe was born in the Irish province of [[Ulster]], almost certainly in the [[County Antrim]] market town [[Ballyclare]] where his father hailed from.<ref name=endurance /> The family later moved to [[Kings Norton]], Birmingham, England, where he attended grammar school. <ref name=coolantarctica>{{cite web |title=Dr. James Archibald McIlroy (1879-1968)  - Biographical notes |url=https://www.coolantarctica.com/Antarctica%20fact%20file/History/biography/mcilroy_james.php |website=Cool Antarctica}}</ref>\n\nAfter McIlroy earned his medical degree at [[Birmingham University]], he was for a brief time a surgeon at [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham|Queen Elizabeth Hospital in Birmingham]]. He spent several of the following years practicing medicine in [[Egypt]], in [[Japan]], and as a ship's surgeon on cruise ships in and around the [[East Indies]].\n\n==First Shackleton expedition==\nIn 1914, McIlroy, along with [[Alexander Macklin]], were the two physicians assigned under Shackleton on 'Endurance', the Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition, despite suffering from [[malaria]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. James McIlroy |url=https://eshackleton.com/2014/07/11/dr-james-mcilroy/ |website=Shackleton}}</ref> Known by the nickname of Mick during the expediton, McIlroy was described by ''Endurance'' author [[Alfred Lansing]] as \"a handsome, aristocratic-looking individual\" who was seen by his fellow crew as a \"man of the world\". He was known to entertain his crew mates with the stories of his exploits sailing around the world.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lansing |first1=Alfred |title=Endurance |date=2014 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=978-0-465-06288-1 |page=50 |archivedate=1959}}</ref> McIlroy was also in charge of a sled-dog team when the expedition was cast away on the [[Weddell Sea]]. He also played the banjo in the team's musical ensemble.<ref name=coolantarctica /> After the castaways found a refuge on [[Elephant Island]], McIlroy was the surgeon performing the amputation of [[Perce Blackborow]]'s [[gangrene|gangrenous]] toes, with Macklin serving as [[anestheologist]], carefully administering a tiny quantity of salvaged [[chloroform]] as [[anaesthesia]]. After the rescue of McIlroy and his comrades, the physician was awarded the Silver [[Polar Medal]].\n\n==Second Shackleton expedition==\nIn 1921 he signed up as a surgeon with Shackleton on another polar expedition, 'Quest', (the [[Shackleton-Rowett Expedition]]); Shacketon died on board ship off [[South Georgia Island]], however, and the mission was completed by explorer [[Frank Wild]] (1873-1939).\n\n==Military service==\nDuring [[World War I]], he was badly wounded at [[Ypres]]. \n\nIn [[World War II]], McIlroy was serving on the [[SS Oronsay (1925)|''S.S. Oronsay'']] when it was torpedoed off the coast of West Africa, spending five days on an open boat before being rescued by the French ship ''Dumont d\u2019Urville''. \n\n==Later life==\nAfter the war, he remained a ship's surgeon well into his late seventies, working for the [[P&O (company)|P&O]] and [[Clan Line]] shipping lines. <ref name=coolantarctica /> He died, at the age of 89, in [[Surrey]], England.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1990 the [[UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee]] named a peak after McIlroy. [[McIlroy Peak]] rises to 745 metres (2,440 ft) west of [[Husvik Harbour]] and 0.8 nautical miles (1.5 km) south of [[Mount Barren]], South Georgia\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927151203/http://www.visitandlearn.co.uk/factfiles/obit19.asp HMS ENDURANCE TRACKING PROJECT]\n* \"Endurance, Shackleton's Incredible Voyage\", pp.&nbsp;206\u2013207; Alfred Lansing\n\n{{Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McIlroy, James}}\n[[Category:British surgeons]]\n[[Category:Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''James Archibald McIlroy''' (3 November 1879 &ndash; 27 July 1968<ref name=endurance>{{cite web|title=James Archibald McIlroy|url=http://www.enduranceobituaries.co.uk/mcilroy.htm|work=enduranceobituaries.co.uk|accessdate=3 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306064659/http://www.enduranceobituaries.co.uk/mcilroy.htm|archivedate=6 March 2012}}</ref>) was a British [[surgeon]] and a member of [[Ernest Shackleton]]'s crew on the [[Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition]] (1914-1916). \n\n==Early life and career==\nHe was born in the Irish province of [[Ulster]], almost certainly in the [[County Antrim]] market town [[Ballyclare]] where his father hailed from.<ref name=endurance /> The family later moved to [[Kings Norton]], Birmingham, England, where he attended grammar school. <ref name=coolantarctica>{{cite web |title=Dr. James Archibald McIlroy (1879-1968)  - Biographical notes |url=https://www.coolantarctica.com/Antarctica%20fact%20file/History/biography/mcilroy_james.php |website=Cool Antarctica}}</ref>\n\nAfter McIlroy earned his medical degree at [[Birmingham University]], he was for a brief time a surgeon at [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham|Queen Elizabeth Hospital in Birmingham]]. He spent several of the following years practicing medicine in [[Egypt]], in [[Japan]], and as a ship's surgeon on cruise ships in and around the [[East Indies]].\n\n==First Shackleton expedition==\nIn 1914, he along with [[Alexander Macklin]] were the two physicians assigned under Shackleton on 'Endurance', the Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition, despite suffering from [[malaria]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. James McIlroy |url=https://eshackleton.com/2014/07/11/dr-james-mcilroy/ |website=Shackleton}}</ref> Known by the nickname of Mick during the expediton, McIlroy was described by ''Endurance'' author [[Alfred Lansing]] as \"a handsome, aristocratic-looking individual\" who was seen by his fellow crew as a \"man of the world\". He was known to entertain his crewmmate with the stories of his exploits sailing around the world.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lansing |first1=Alfred |title=Endurance |date=2014 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=978-0-465-06288-1 |page=50 |archivedate=1959}}</ref> McIlroy was also in charge of a sled-dog team when the expedition was cast away on the [[Weddell Sea]]. He also played the banjo in the team's musical ensemble.<ref name=coolantarctica /> After the castaways found a refuge on [[Elephant Island]], McIlroy was the surgeon performing the amputation of [[Perce Blackborow]]'s [[gangrene|gangrenous]] toes, with Macklin serving as [[anestheologist]], carefully administering a tiny quantity of salvaged [[chloroform]] as [[anaesthesia]]. After the rescue of McIlroy and his comrades, the physician was awarded the Silver [[Polar Medal]].\n\n==Second Shackleton expedition==\nIn 1921 he signed up as a surgeon with Shackleton on another polar expedition, 'Quest', (the [[Shackleton-Rowett Expedition]]); Shacketon died on board ship off [[South Georgia Island]], however, and the mission was completed by explorer [[Frank Wild]] (1873-1939).\n\n==Military service==\nDuring [[World War I]], he was badly wounded at [[Ypres]]. \n\nIn [[World War II]], McIlroy was serving on the [[SS Oronsay (1925)|''S.S. Oronsay'']] when it was torpedoed off the coast of West Africa, spending five days on an open boat before being rescued by the French ship ''Dumont d\u2019Urville''. \n\n==Later life==\nAfter the war, he remained a ship's surgeon well into his late seventies, working for the [[P&O (company)|P&O]] and [[Clan Line]] shipping lines. <ref name=coolantarctica /> He died, at the age of 89, in [[Surrey]], England.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1990 the [[UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee]] named a peak after McIlroy. [[McIlroy Peak]] rises to 745 metres (2,440 ft) west of [[Husvik Harbour]] and 0.8 nautical miles (1.5 km) south of [[Mount Barren]], South Georgia\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927151203/http://www.visitandlearn.co.uk/factfiles/obit19.asp HMS ENDURANCE TRACKING PROJECT]\n* \"Endurance, Shackleton's Incredible Voyage\", pp.&nbsp;206\u2013207; Alfred Lansing\n\n{{Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McIlroy, James}}\n[[Category:British surgeons]]\n[[Category:Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Wolfcruiser", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFirst Shackleton expedition", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_McIlroy_(surgeon)"}
